{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti** (by Manu) extensively discusses the privileges and duties of the Brahmana (Brahmin) as the highest varṇa. In Chapter 1, it assigns specific duties such as teaching and studying the Veda, performing sacrifices for oneself and others, and giving/receiving alms.[^1] It also asserts the Brahmina's superiority and lordship over creation due to origin from the highest limb (mouth of Puruṣa), seniority, and Veda preservation.[^2]\n\n**Āṅgirasa Smṛti** (by Aṅgirasa) engages with Brahmin duties and privileges in ritual and purity contexts throughout its single chapter. Examples include requirements for purity (*āśauca*) before Vedic rites,[^3] the exclusive right to Veda recitation (under a heading explicitly titled \"The Brahmin's Right to the Veda\"),[^4] and permissions needed from Brahmins for certain ascetic or ritual acts.[^5]\n\nNo other works in the corpus returned relevant results for these topics in searches across the English translations.[^6]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-71a5c2).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-7c0113).\n\n[^3]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-5b9e77).\n\n[^4]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-dd2905).\n\n[^5]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-fd7069). (See also surrounding verses on Brahmin permissions for rites.)\n\n[^6]: Based on full-corpus searches for \"Brahmin,\" \"Brahmana,\" and related phrases, which exclusively matched these two works.",
